1. Introduction¶

1.1 Framing the Problem¶

The purpose of this analysis examines the correlation between median house value and three independent factors including household, median income and population. Linear regression and exploratory data analysis methods will help comprehend the strength of influence these independent factors have on median house value data in a chosen dataset.

2.2 Creating three Seaborn scatter plots of median house value vs. median income, population and number of households¶

In [235]:
# Scatter plot for median house value vs. median income
sns.scatterplot(x='median_income', y='median_house_value', data=data)
plt.title('Median House Value vs. Median Income')
plt.show()

Interpretation of the graph and insights: Higher incomes tend to raise home values but the $500,000 limit on house prices might produce misleading analysis. The majority of clustering points happen between areas with income levels 0-8 and house value ranges from 100k to 300k while the dataset contains some outliers. The observed pattern is mostly linear but the bounded data points along with the inconsistent dispersion can affect the validity of regression models requiring either log transformation or outlier management or alternative robust regression methods.

In [236]:
# Scatter plot for median house value vs. population
sns.scatterplot(x='population', y='median_house_value', data=data)
plt.title('Median House Value vs. Population')
plt.show()

Interpretation of the graph and insights: The data shows weak population value correlation while most data clustering remain within 0-10,000 population range with a price cap at $500,000 which affects the results. The data distribution becomes too erratic after reaching 10,000 population therefore research results cannot provide dependable predictions. Results become significantly skewed from the price cap while the wide variability of the data shows population works poorly as a single predictor.

In [237]:
# Scatter plot for median house value vs. number of households
sns.scatterplot(x='households', y='median_house_value', data=data)
plt.title('Median House Value vs. Number of Households')
plt.show()

Interpretation of the graph and insights: Most data points fall within the 0-2,000 household bracket while the $500,000 limit skews analysis results. This indicates no clear relationship exists between these two variables. The distribution of house values becomes less reliable after exceeding 2,000 households. The price limitation influences outcome results and large variance shows that the household count independently fails to produce accurate house price predictions.

2.4 Describing the 4 variables¶

Median Income
Meaning: The median income of households in a given area.
Range: The measurement shows minimal variations from zero to 15 (with results expected in tens of thousands).
Household income creates a strong positive relationship with median house values because home prices rise when incomes increase.

Population
Meaning: describes all residents in a particular geographical region.
Range: 0 to 35,000+ people.
The data points show minimal link between median household income and house value while most observations collect in the 0-10,000 range.

Number of Households
Meaning: The total enumeration of resident families in a specific region.
Range: 0 to 6,000+ households.
Similar to population counts the number of households shows weak correlation with the prices of houses and forms tight data clusters below 2,000 households.

Median House Value
Meaning: Median home price in a given area.
Range: 0 to 500,000 (capped).
The relationship between income and this variable is positive but population and households demonstrate minimal impact on its values because it has an upper boundary at 500,000.

3. Data Preprocessing¶

Filter out records with median_house_value = 500001 since it seems to be a cap for the median_house_value.

Conclusion¶

To show a more precise model correlation between median house value and its independent variables consisting of median income and population and number of households the price cap restriction was removed. Previously the restriction caused data to cluster at the upper bound which distorted the regression model line and reduced its performance capabilities.

The data restriction removal strengthens the connection between median income and house value while median income stands as the most reliable forecasting factor for house prices. The model predictions become more accurate after eliminating the cap because it leads to decreased Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE). The predictive power of population and number of households remains minimal due to house prices being unaffected by primary influences from these metrics. These models still demonstrate high variance because house prices align more strongly with income than they do with population size or count of households even though their MSE and MAE show some minor improvement.
